And the wall collapsed ...
Here's a quiz for history buffs: 20 years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4th.
Which one do you remember best and which had the most significant consequences for the planet?
a) The bloody crackdown in Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few people answer c).
Because the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made the headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and consequently to the reformation of the post-war international order.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was a moment of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins are unknown.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement for change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader heading Poland, General Jaruzelski, thought that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to face alone.
Why not turn to the Polish opposition, he said - if not to find a solution - at least to share the responsibility of the situation with them?
After six months of bargaining, he reached a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections and Solidarnosc would be allowed to participate in them.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarnosc) did not for a single moment consider that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they did not imagine that they would be driven from power.
Yet, that is exactly what happened.
In retrospect, it is surprising that there could have been any doubts.
Solidarnosc took a bold stance in its campaign.
A famous poster, repurposed for the occasion, from a classic western, The Train Will Whistle Three Times, was a great success: it shows a Gary Cooper holding a ballot paper instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4th was the day of judgment.
On this bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving way to summer, voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one last perversity that turned into an involuntary act of self-humiliation.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting their preferred candidates, had to cross out the names of those they did not want - in other words, all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere one looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had long been waiting for, revenge for December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarnosc, and threw its leaders in prison.
The revolution by the pen!
Wielded with style, the pen that eventually triumphs over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Some voters literally tore up their ballots, thus effectively decapitating the old regime with a single stroke.
Others savored the moment, perhaps taking a puff on a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "Look, this apparatchik got rich off our shortages," Pfft!
Pfft!
On the other hand, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
Across all of Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most relied on their monopoly in the media to get their message across: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist".
It can be said to its credit that the regime acknowledged its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three o'clock in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the party's main leaders to tell them: "Our defeat is total", a political solution must be found".
This meant that he wanted neither violence nor fraud, and the communists would have to live with the election results.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe knew that Solidarnosc would win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern Bloc.
The election in Poland was extremely encouraging for anticommunists around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what had seemed impossible just a few days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began tearing down the fences erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "European Common Home" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously acknowledged: "We didn't see it coming".
The Cold War had lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom erupted.
